<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910403-0021</DOCNO><DOCID>910403-0021.</DOCID><HL>   Major Canadian Banks   Cut Their Prime Rates</HL><DATE>04/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   T.BMO</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)CANADIAN ECONOMIC, MONETARY NEWS AND ANALYSIS (CEA)CANADIAN ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (CEM)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)</IN><RE>CANADA (CN)</RE><LP>   OTTAWA -- Most major Canadian banks, responding toCanada's weak economy, cut their prime lending rates half apercentage point to 10 3/4%, effective today.   The move reduced the prime rate to its lowest level inmore than two and a half years. The prime rate is the basefor various bank lending charges.</LP><TEXT>   The latest rate cut was initiated by the Bank of Montreal,which has frequently taken the lead in prime rate changes inthe past year. Bank of Montreal reduced its rate to 10 3/4%from 11%. The prime rates of other major banks had been 111/4%.   Lloyd Atkinson, Bank of Montreal's chief economist, saidrecent economic data confirmed that Canada's recessiondeepened at &quot;a quickening pace&quot; in the January-March period.&quot;The need for lower interest rates under these conditions isapparent,&quot; he said.   The recession started in the April-June period last year.The government and many analysts predict that an economicrecovery will start this summer.   The prime rate has fallen steadily since last July when,for most banks, it was 14 3/4%.</TEXT></DOC>